name: NGC 188   C1
text: Caldwell 1, also known as NGC 188, is an open cluster, a group of stars that were all formed from the same large cloud of gas and are therefore all roughly the same age. One of the oldest open clusters known, Caldwell 1 is estimated to be at least 6.8 billion years old.

name: NGC 4236   C3
text: Caldwell 3, also known as NGC 4236, is one of at least 34 gravitationally bound galaxies in the Ursa Major galaxy group. It is a barred spiral galaxy, possessing an elongated lane of stars that cuts through its center.

name: NGC 7023 C4 Iris Nebula
text: The Iris Nebula, also known as Caldwell 4 or NGC 7023, is a reflection nebula. Its color comes from the scattered light of its central star. Reflection nebulae are made of particles smaller than dust particles on Earth that diffuse light from nearby stars.

name: IC 342  C5
text: Spiral galaxy IC 342, also known as Caldwell 5, displays intertwined tendrils of glowing, rosy dust in arms that wrap around a blue core of hot gas and stars. Difficult to see from Earth because of thick cosmic gas, dark dust, and glowing stars in the way, it is nicknamed the Hidden Galaxy.

name: NGC 6543 C6  Cat's Eye Nebula
text: Produced by a dying star, the Cat's Eye Nebula, also called Caldwell 6, is one of the most complex planetary nebulae known. This image reveals a pattern of concentric rings around the central star. Each "ring" is actually the edge of a spherical bubble of material ejected by the star.

name: NGC 2403 C7  Galaxy SN 2004dj
text: Spiral galaxy Caldwell 7, also called NGC 2403, contains pinkish, glowing clouds filled with hot areas of ionized hydrogen, which can form thousands of stars over a couple million years. The  bright "star" in the upper right corner of this image is actually a supernova that was observed in 2004.

name: Cave Nebula Sh2-155   C9
text: A yawning mouth of gas and dust gives the Cave Nebula its nickname. This emission nebula, also called Caldwell 9, is formed of glowing, ionized gases and is actually part of a much larger cloud of gas and dust, Cepheus B. The bright arc that forms the cave's mouth is an active stellar birthplace.

name: NGC 7635 C11  Bubble Nebula
text: An enormous bubble is being blown into space by a super-hot, massive star. The Bubble Nebula, or Caldwell 11, is roughly seven light-years across and is located 7,100 light-years away in the constellation Cassiopeia.

name: NGC 6946  C12 Fireworks Galaxy
text: The Fireworks galaxy (Caldwell 12 or NGC 6946) was named for its propensity for producing supernovae. This spiral galaxy's arms have been home to 10 observed supernovae since 1917. A tight, glowing ring around the galaxy's nucleus has likely been making stars for nearly 20 million years.

name: NGC 6826   C15 Blinking Planetary Nebula
text: The Blinking Planetary, also known as Caldwell 15 or NGC 6826, is a greenish orb of gas and dust, the outer layers of the burned-out star that jettisoned into space. The core of that star exists as a white dwarf at the center of the nebula.

name: NGC 4449  C21
text: Caldwell 21, also known as NGC 4449, is an irregular dwarf galaxy. In the dusty pink areas, new stars are flaring into life. Star formation activity is so intense here that astronomers refer to it as a starburst.

name: NGC 7662 Blue Snowball Nebula  C22
text: The Snowball Nebula or Blue Snowball Nebula, also known as Caldwell 22 and NGC 7662, is a planetary nebula. When a medium-mass star like our Sun runs out of fuel, its outer layers of gas puff away into space to form a planetary nebula, leaving a small white dwarf at the nebula's center.

name: NGC 891  C23
text: If we could travel across space and time to see our own galaxy from the outside looking in, it would probably look a lot like Caldwell 23. This spiral galaxy, also called NGC 891, has been used to learn more about the structure and evolution of spiral galaxies.

name: NGC 1275   C24 Perseus A
text: Hubble was the first to resolve giant but delicate filaments of gas shaped by strong magnetic fields around Perseus A — an elliptical galaxy also known as Caldwell 24 and NGC 1275. The galaxy's central black hole generates unusually powerful X-ray and radio emission.

name: NGC 2419  C25
text: Unlike most of our Milky Way's globular clusters, which are huge, spherical clouds of old stars that formed with the galaxy, Caldwell 25 (NGC 2419) may not be from around here. Scientists surmise that the cluster may be the remains of a small galaxy that was captured and disrupted by the Milky Way.

name: NGC 4244  C26 Silver Needle Galaxy
text: The Silver Needle (Caldwell 26 or NGC 4244) is a spiral galaxy with a strangely thin appearance. The edge-on galaxy's central bulge is much less pronounced than we see in most spiral galaxies and its halo is very faint.

name: NGC 6888 C27 Crescent Nebula
text: This is a close-up of a section of the Crescent Nebula (Caldwell 27 or NGC 6888) that's about 3 light-years across. The cloudy, mottled shell surrounds an extremely hot and short-lived type of star called a Wolf-Rayet, which is unleashing a powerful stellar wind.

name: NGC 7331  C30
text: The majestic spiral galaxy Caldwell 30, also cataloged as NGC 7331, has magnificent spiral arms featuring dark, obscuring dust lanes; bright, bluish clusters of massive young stars; and the telltale reddish glow of active star-forming regions.

name: NGC 4631  C32 Whale Galaxy
text: This stream of stars embedded in cosmic clouds is part of what's known as the Whale galaxy (Caldwell 32 or NGC 4631). Our edge-on view of this galaxy masks the spiral arms that extend outward into space, each overflowing with sparkling stars.

name: NGC 6992  C33 Eastern Veil Nebula
text: This image captures part of an extensive supernova remnant known as the Veil Nebula (or the Cygnus Loop). Caldwell 33 is often called the Eastern Veil (including regions known as NGC 6992 and NGC 6995). The Veil Nebula is the cosmic shrapnel from a star that exploded several thousand years ago.

name: NGC 6960   C34 West Veil Nebula
text: In this small piece of the Veil Nebula, also known as Caldwell 34 and NGC 6960, wisps of gas are part of what remains of a star that was once 20 times more massive than our Sun. A fast-moving blast wave from the star's explosion is plowing into a wall of interstellar gas, causing it to glow.

name: NGC 4889  C35
text: The giant elliptical galaxy Caldwell 35, also known as NGC 4889, is about two and a half times larger than the Milky Way. Hidden in the heart of this tranquil-seeming galaxy lies a supermassive black hole with a mass 21 billion times greater than the Sun.

name: NGC 4565  C38 Needle Galaxy
text: Caldwell 38, or NGC 4565, is nicknamed the Needle galaxy, because in most telescopes it looks as thin and sharp as a pin. It is a spiral galaxy, but because it is seen almost perfectly edge-on, its spiral structure is concealed.

name: NGC 2392 C39 Eskimo Nebula
text: This planetary nebula, Caldwell 39, contains the glowing remains of a dying Sun-like star. The bright, central region is material being blown away by the nebula's central star.

name: NGC 7006 C42
text: Globular cluster Caldwell 42, also known as NGC 7006, is a relic of the Milky Way's earliest years. Born as the galaxy was forming, these clusters provide a glimpse backward in time and provide a hint of what the Milky Way was like billions of years ago.

name: NGC 7814  C43 Little Sombrero
text: Nicknamed the Little Sombrero, Caldwell 43 (or NGC 7814) is an edge-on galaxy featuring a bright central bulge, a thin disk full of dust, and a glowing halo of gas and stars that sprawls out into space.

name: NGC 7479 Propeller Galaxy C44
text: In the Propeller galaxy, also known as Caldwell 44 and NGC 7479, the tightly wound arms of the barred spiral galaxy create a backward "S" as they spin in a counter-clockwise direction.

name: NGC 2261 C46 Hubble's Variable Nebula
text: Hubble's Variable Nebula, also called Caldwell 46 or NGC 2261, is lit by a massive, young star dubbed R Monocerotis. The nebula's brightness changes depending on how the surrounding dust blocks the star.

name: NGC 6934 C47
text: Globular cluster Caldwell 47, or NGC 6934, is made up of many thousands of stars held together by gravity. Star clusters like this one encircle our galaxy like bees buzzing around a hive, typically in the galaxy's halo.

name: NGC 7009 Saturn Nebula C55
text: The Saturn Nebula, also known as Caldwell 55 and NGC 7009, is made up of the outer gaseous layers of a dying star. When a medium-mass star exhausts its nuclear fuel, it will swell up and shrug off its outer layers until only its small, hot core (known as a white dwarf) remains.

name: NGC 6822 C57 Barnard's Galaxy Hubble-V & X Nebula
text: More than 2 million light-years away lies the irregular dwarf galaxy Caldwell 57, or NGC 6822. This image, taken to study the galaxy's stellar populations, shows a field of stars in the galaxy's outskirts. The dark streak is an artifact of Hubble's detector.

name: NGC 3242 Cosmic Eye C59 Ghost of Jupiter
text: Caldwell 59, a planetary nebula also cataloged as NGC 3242, is sometimes called the Ghost of Jupiter for its faint resemblance to the gas giant planet, though it is much larger and farther away. It formed when a dying medium-mass star threw off its outer layers.

name: NGC 4038  C60 Antennae Galaxies
text: The two merging spiral galaxies that comprise the Antennae galaxies, Caldwell 60 and 61, began their interaction only a few hundred million years ago. Over the course of the merger, billions of stars will be formed.

name: NGC 247  C62 Neddle's Eye Galaxy
text: The Needle's Eye galaxy, also known as Caldwell 62 and NGC 247, is a dwarf spiral galaxy. It was given its nickname because one end of it features a strange void of stars (not seen in this Hubble close-up of the galaxy's starry center).

name: NGC 7293 C63 Helix Nebula
text: The Helix Nebula, also known as Caldwell 63 and NGC 7293, is one of the closest planetary nebulae, made up of glowing gas around a dying, Sun-like star. The Helix looks like a bubble, but is actually more like a tunnel of gas pointing back toward the star.

name: NGC 253 C65 Sculptor Galaxy
text: In the Sculptor galaxy, also called Caldwell 65 or NGC 253, dark dust clouds and scattered massive stars obscure much of the galaxy's detail. A starburst galaxy, it contains a vast number of rapidly forming stars.

name: NGC 1097  C67
text: Barred spiral galaxy Caldwell 67, or NGC 1097, contains a lane of stars and dust that extends away from the bright center toward the lower left and upper right of this image. The galaxy's vast spiral arms stretch much farther beyond this close-up Hubble view, over 100,000 light-years through space.

name: NGC 6302 C69 Bug Nebula
text: In the Bug or Butterfly nebula, also known as Caldwell 69 and NGC 6302, layers of gas are being ejected from a Sun-like star that has exhausted its nuclear fuel. The gas is tearing across space at more than 600,000 miles an hour — fast enough to travel from Earth to the Moon in 24 minutes.

name: NGC 300 C70
text: What resemble grains of sand in this image are individual stars embedded in the heart of the nearby spiral galaxy Caldwell 70, also called NGC 300. This image shows the inner region of the galaxy and the galaxy's bright, densely packed core surrounded by tendrils of dark dust.

name: NGC 3132 C74 Southern Ring Nebula
text: This image of the Southern Ring Nebula, or Caldwell 74, clearly shows two stars near the center of the nebula: a bright, white one, and a fainter companion to its upper right. The faint star is actually the star that has ejected the material that forms the nebula.

name: NGC 5128 C77  Centaurus A
text: This image captures a turbulent firestorm of star birth along a nearly edge-on dust disk girdling nearby galaxy Centaurus A, also called Caldwell 77. Brilliant clusters of young, blue stars lie along the edge of the dark dust lane.

name: NGC 3201 C79
text: This image features stars at the center of the glittering globular cluster Caldwell 79, or NGC 3201. Globular clusters are dense, gravitationally bound packs of stars that roam the fringes of the galaxy. Most of the Milky Way's globular clusters are estimated to be over 10 billion years old.

name: NGC 5139 Omega Centauri C80
text: This view shows stars at the heart of Omega Centauri or Caldwell 80, one of roughly 150 globular clusters in our Milky Way galaxy. The behemoth stellar grouping is the biggest and brightest globular cluster in the Milky Way, and one of the few that can be seen by the unaided eye.

name: NGC 6397  C86  Globular Cluster
text: Globular cluster Caldwell 86, also called NGC 6397, is a swarm of hundreds of thousands of stars. The cluster is dated at a staggering 13.4 billion years old.

name: NGC 2867 C90
text: Caldwell 90, or NGC 2867, is a planetary nebula, formed in the late stages of the evolution of a Sun-like star. The star's outer layers of gas were ejected, and the star itself became a hot, dense white dwarf.

name: NGC 3372 C92 Eta Carina Nebula
text: This close-up view shows only a three-light-year-wide portion of the entire Carina Nebula, or Caldwell 92, which has a diameter of over 200 light-years. Located 8,000 light-years from Earth, the nebula can be seen in the southern sky with the naked eye.

name: NGC 6752 C93
text: This image shows stars in a small part of the globular cluster Caldwell 93, also called NGC 6752. The stars in this ancient swarm are thought to be about 10 billion years old.

name: NGC 4755 C94 Jewel Box Cluster
text: The Jewel Box Cluster, also called Caldwell 94 and NGC 4755, is a collection of just over 100 loosely bound stars. Stars in an open cluster like this only remain together for a limited time, gradually dispersing into space.

name: IC2944 Collinder 249  THACKERAY'S GLOBULES C100
text: Dense, opaque dust clouds, known as "Thackeray's Globules," are silhouetted against nearby bright stars in open star cluster Caldwell 100. The globules — made of gas, molecules, and cosmic dust— are so dense that they block the light behind them.

name: NGC 6744 C101
text: Spiral galaxy Caldwell 101, also called NGC 6744, is one of the relatively few large spiral galaxies in the neighboring universe. Its yellowish core is dominated by the light from old, cool stars, and its spiral arms are littered with dust that gives birth to star formation.

name: NGC 2070  C103 30 doradus 30 Dor Tarantula Nebula
text: This is a close-up view of a star-birth region called the 30 Doradus Nebula, also called Caldwell 103 or NGC 2070. The giant stellar factory lies 170,000 light-years away inside a nearby galaxy known as the Large Magellanic Cloud. The image reveals glowing clouds of hydrogen and dark filamentary structures of dust.

name: NGC 362  C104  Star Cluster
text: Caldwell 104, or NGC 362, is a gravitationally bound globular cluster of stars. Most globular clusters are much older than most stars in their host galaxy, but the stars in Caldwell 104 are unusual ― they appear to be 2 billion to 3 billion years younger than stars in other Milky Way globulars.

name: NGC 4833  C105
text: Caldwell 105, or NGC 4833, is one of the over 150 known globular star clusters inthe Milky Way. These objects contain some of the oldest stars in our galaxy.

name: NGC 104 C106  47 Tucanae
text: This image shows globular star cluster 47 Tucanae, also called Caldwell 106 or NGC 104. The entire cluster contains about a million stars, with many packed tightly in the core.

name: NGC 3195  C109
text: Caldwell 109, or NGC 3195, resembles a phantom snowball. The glowing shroud of gas was shed by its central star in a final act before dying. Our own Sun is destined to meet a similar fate in about 6 billion years.

name: NGC 1952 Crab Nebula M1
text: At the center of the Crab Nebula, also called Messier 1 or NGC 1952, sits a stellar remnant called a neutron star that has about the same mass as the Sun compressed into a sphere only a few miles across. Spinning 30 times a second, the neutron star shoots out beams of energy that make it look like it's pulsating.

name: NGC 7089 M2
text: Messier 2, or NGC 7089, is a globular cluster, a spherical group of stars tightly bound together by gravity. With a diameter of roughly 175 light-years, and a population of 150,000 stars, M2 is one of the largest clusters of its kind and one of the oldest known in the Milky Way.

name: NGC 5272 M3
text: Globular cluster Messier 3, or NGC 5272, is known to contain over 500,000 stars, and more variable stars ― 274 ― than any other cluster. Certain variable stars are known to brighten and dim in a predictable way over time, allowing astronomers to use these stars to calculate cosmic distances.

name: NGC 6121 M4
text: Messier 4, or NGC 6121, is a huge, spherical collection of stars known as a globular cluster and, at just 5,500 light-years away, the closest globular cluster to Earth. Home to more than 100,000 stars, the cluster is predicted to contain up to 40,000 white dwarfs — the cores of ancient, dead stars.

name: NGC 5904 M5
text: This image of globular cluster Messier 5, or NGC 5904, features over 100,000 stars. A majority formed more than 12 billion years ago, but there are some unexpected young stars on the scene ― perhaps created by collisions and interactions between stars in the packed cluster.

name: NGC 6523 Lagoon Nebula M8
text: This image zooms into the heart of a vast star-forming region called the Lagoon Nebula, also called Messier 8 or NGC 6523. A massive young star is blasting radiation and stellar winds, carving shapes into the surrounding gas and dust.

name: NGC 6333 M9
text: Messier 9, or NGC 6333, is one of the closest globular clusters to the center of our Milky Way galaxy. M9's proximity to the center of the Milky Way has warped the cluster's shape, so the ball of gravitationally bound stars appears less spherical than it typically would.

name: NGC 6254 M10
text: The stars in globular clusters like Messier 10, or NGC 6254, are thought to have formed together, so they should all be roughly the same age. Yet M10 contains many stars that appear to be far younger than their neighbors. These stars were created either by collisions or interactions between stars.

name: NGC 6705 M11 Wild Duck Cluster
text: Known as the Wild Duck Cluster for the roughly V-shaped arrangement of its brightest stars, the open cluster Messier 11, also called NGC 6705, is a group of stars that are only loosely bound by gravity. M11's 2,900 stars will eventually drift apart.

name: NGC 6218   M12
text: Globular clusters like Messier 12 have high concentrations of gravitationally bound stars, so they often contain binary systems — two stars orbiting around each other. Some of these systems give off X-rays, and many have been detected in M12, also called NGC 6218.

name: NGC 6205 M13
text: Like shiny flakes sparkling in a snow globe, over 100,000 stars whirl within the globular cluster Messier 13, also called NGC 6205, one of the brightest star clusters visible from the Northern Hemisphere.

name: NGC 6402 M14
text: This image captures a portion of globular cluster Messier 14, home to over 150,000 stars. M14, also called NGC 6402, is located 29,000 light-years away from Earth in the constellation Ophiuchus.

name: NGC 7078 M15
text: These stars belong to the globular cluster M15, also called NGC 7078. Nestled among them is an astronomical oddity, the first planetary nebula found in a globular cluster.

name: NGC 6611 M16  Eagle Nebula
text: Hubble's view of the "Pillars of Creation" in the Eagle Nebula, also called Messier 16 or NGC 6611, displays three giant columns of cold gas giving birth to new stars. The pillars are bathed in the scorching ultraviolet light from a cluster of young, massive stars beyond the top of the image.

name: NGC 6618 Omega/Swan Nebula M17
text: This image captures a small region within the Swan Nebula, also called Messier 17 or NGC 6618, a hotbed of star formation. The wave-like patterns of gas have been sculpted and illuminated by a torrent of ultraviolet radiation from young, massive stars, which lie outside the picture to the upper left.

name: NGC 6723 M19
text: Messier 19, also called NGC 6723, is a globular cluster, a group of stars tightly bound together by gravity. These clusters are usually spherical but some, like M19, have a slightly elongated shape.

name: NGC 6514 M20 Trifid Nebula
text: The Trifid Nebula, also called Messier 20 or NGC 6514, is a stellar nursery criss-crossed by huge, dark lanes of dust. This image provides a close-up view of the center of the nebula, near the intersection of the dust bands, and a group of recently formed, massive, bright stars.

name: NGC 6656 M22
text: Messier 22, also called NGC 6656, is one of about 150 globular star clusters in the Milky Way. Located just 10,000 light-years away in the constellation Sagittarius, it is one of the closest globular clusters to Earth.

name: NGC 6853 M27  Dumbbell Nebula
text: This image captures a small part of the Dumbbell Nebula, also called Messier 27 or NGC 6853, which resides more than 1,200 light-years away. Known as a planetary nebula, it is the result of an old star that has shed its outer layers in a glowing display of color. It was the first planetary nebula ever discovered.

name: NGC 6626 M28
text: Messier 28, also called NGC 6626, is a globular cluster, a group of stars bound together by gravity. It is the first of its kind known to contain a millisecond pulsar, a dense neutron star that rotates rapidly and emits radiation from its poles, making it look like it's pulsing from Earth's view.

name: NGC 7099 M30
text: Messier 30, or NGC 7099, is a globular cluster, a group of stars bound tightly together by gravity. Although globular clusters are mainly populated by old stars, the density of the stellar swarm leads to collisions and interactions that can appear to rejuvenate some stars.

name: Andromeda Galaxy M31, NGC224
text: Over 100 million stars are on display in this portion of the Andromeda galaxy, located over 2 million light-years away. This portrait of our galactic neighbor, also called Messier 31 or NGC 224, is the largest image yet assembled by Hubble.

name: Dwarf Elliptical Galaxy NGC 221 M32
text: Countless stars, from the compact core to the less dense outskirts, are packed into this image of a portion of elliptical galaxy Messier 32. Also called NGC 221, the galaxy is located 2.5 million light-years from Earth.

name: Triangulum Galaxy M33, NGC598
text: This mosaic captures the nearby Triangulum galaxy, also called Messier 33 or NGC 598. Striking areas of star birth glow bright blue throughout the galaxy, particularly in beautiful nebulae of hot gas like star-forming region NGC 604 in the lower left.

name: NGC 1976 Orion Nebula M42
text: The Orion Nebula, also called Messier 42 or NGC 1976, is the nearest star-forming region to Earth. Massive, young stars are shaping the nebula with their winds and radiation. Pillars of dense gas may be the homes of budding stars. The bright central region is the home of the four heftiest stars in the nebula.

name: NGC 1982 M43
text: A massive star (center) illuminates the nebula Messier 43 and sculpts its landscape of dust and gas with its radiation. The nebula, also called NGC 1982, is part of the massive stellar nursery called the Orion Molecular Cloud Complex.

name: Pleiades M45
text: Wispy tendrils of an interstellar cloud are being destroyed by one of the brightest stars in the Seven Sisters or Pleiades open cluster, also known as Messier 45. The star's light reflects off the surface of dark clouds of cold gas laced with dust, producing a reflection nebula.

name: NGC 4472 M49
text: Unlike spiral galaxies that have well-defined structures and picturesque spiral arms, elliptical galaxies like Messier 49, or NGC 4472, are fairly featureless, with little structure. The stars in elliptical galaxies are usually much older than those in spiral galaxies.

name: NGC5194 Whirlpool Galaxy M51a
text: The Whirlpool galaxy, also called Messier 51 and NGC 5194, features brilliant curving arms, a hallmark of so-called grand-design spiral galaxies. The Whirlpool's arms may be so prominent because of a close encounter with NGC 5195, the small, yellowish galaxy at the tip of one of the arms.

name: NGC 5024 Cluster M53
text: Thousands and thousands of brilliant stars make up the globular cluster Messier 53, also called NGC 5024. With its stars bound tightly by gravity, the cluster is roughly spherical and becomes denser toward its heart.

name: NGC 6715  Cluster M54
text: This dense group of stars known as Messier 54 was the first globular cluster found outside our galaxy. M54, also called NGC 6715, belongs to a Milky Way satellite galaxy known as the Sagittarius Dwarf Elliptical galaxy, which will eventually merge with the Milky Way.

name: NGC 6779 Cluster M56
text: Messier 56 is a globular cluster, a group of stars tightly bound by gravity. M56, or NGC 6779, has relatively few elements heavier than hydrogen and helium, which is a sign that its stars were born early in the universe's history.

name: NGC 6720 Ring Nebula M57
text: About a light-year across, the Ring Nebula, also called Messier 57 or NGC 6720, is formed by a dying star floating in a blue haze of hot gas at its center. This image reveals elongated, dark clumps of material embedded in the gas at the edge of the nebula.

name: NGC 4579  M58 Galaxy
text: Messier 58, or NGC 4579, was one of the first galaxies recognized to have a spiral shape. Its core contains high rates of star formation, known as starburst activity. A small ring around the galaxy's nucleus is a region of widespread starburst activity and is a rare phenomenon among galaxies.

name: NGC 4621  M59
text: Messier 59, also called NGC 4621, is one of the largest elliptical galaxies in the Virgo galaxy cluster. A supermassive black hole around 270 million times as massive as the Sun resides at its center.

name: NGC 4649  M60
text: This image captures elliptical galaxy Messier 60 (center) along with the bluish spiral galaxy NGC 4647 (upper right). NGC 4647 is about two-thirds the size of M60, which is also known as NGC 4649, and is much less massive. The two galaxies form a pair known as Arp 116.

name: NGC 4303 M61
text: Messier 61, or NGC 4303, is a barred spiral galaxy. Its spiral arms can be seen in stunning detail, swirling inward to the center of the galaxy, where they form a smaller spiral. In the outer parts of the galaxy, these arms are sprinkled with bright, blue regions where new stars are forming.

name: NGC 6266  M62
text: Made up of gravitationally bound stars, Messier 62, or NGC 6266, is one of the most irregularly shaped globular clusters in our galaxy. This might be because it is one of the closest globular clusters to the galactic center and is affected by galactic tidal forces.

name: NGC 5055 M63 Sunflower Galaxy
text: The Sunflower galaxy, also called Messier 63 or NGC 5055, is a flocculent spiral galaxy, which means it lacks well-defined arms. Although it only has two arms, many more appear to be winding around its yellow core.

name: NGC 4826 M64 Blackeye Galaxy
text: Easily identified by the spectacular band of absorbing dust partially obscuring its bright nucleus, the Black Eye galaxy, also called Messier 64 or NGC 4374, is speckled with hot blue stars that have just formed, as well as pink clouds of glowing hydrogen.

name: NGC 3623  M65
text: Spiral galaxy Messier 65 is located roughly 35 million light-years from Earth in the constellation Leo. Also called NGC 3623, it is a member of the Leo Triplet of galaxies, which are all spirals.

name: NGC 3627  M66
text: Spiral galaxy Messier 66 is a member of the Leo Triplet of galaxies. M66, or NGC 3627, displays asymmetric spiral arms and a core that appears to be off center — features likely caused by the gravitational pull of the other two galaxies in the group.

name: NGC 4590  M68
text: Messier 68, also called NGC 4590, is a dense collection of stars known as a globular cluster. Gravitational attraction amongst the hundreds of thousands or even millions of stars in such a cluster keeps the stars packed tightly together for billions of years.

name: NGC 6637  M69
text: Messier 69, also called NGC 6637, is one of the most metal-rich globular clusters ever observed. Its stars have over 10 times more iron than stars in other globular clusters ― dense, gravitationally bound groups of stars ― of the same age.

name: NGC 6681  M70
text: Quarters are always tight in globular clusters like Messier 70, where gravity binds together hundreds of thousands of stars in a small region of space. M70, or NGC 6681, has undergone a core collapse, which means that even more stars than usual squeeze into the object's core.

name: NGC 6838  M71
text: Messier 71, also called NGC 6838, is puzzling. It has been classified as both an abnormally dense open star cluster and as an unusually loose globular cluster. Today, astronomers think M71 is a young, loosely concentrated globular cluster — one of the smallest of its kind.

name: NGC 6981  M72
text: A globular cluster is an ancient, spherical collection of old stars that are packed closely together. The stars in the cluster orbit around a mutual center of gravity at the cluster's dense core. Messier 72, or NGC 6981, is one of around 150 globular clusters discovered in the Milky Way galaxy.

name: NGC 628 M74
text: Messier 74, or NGC 628, is a grand-design spiral galaxy. Symmetrical spiral arms reach out from the galaxy's central nucleus and are traced by winding dust lanes. The arms are dotted with clusters of young, blue stars and pink regions of glowing, ionized hydrogen.

name: NGC 6864  M75
text: Messier 75 is a globular cluster, a dense group of stars tightly bound together by gravity. In total, there are about 400,000 stars in M75, also called NGC 6864.

name: NGC 650/651  M76 Little Dumbbell Nebula
text: The Little Dumbbell Nebula, also known as Messier 76, is a planetary nebula, an expanding shell of gas around an aging or dying star. It's also known as the Cork Nebula, the Barbell Nebula, as well as both NGC 650 and NGC 651. Only half the nebula appears in this Hubble image.

name: NGC 1068  M77 Cetus A
text: Spiral galaxy Messier 77, also called NGC 1068, is a Seyfert galaxy, or a galaxy with an intensely active center that is obscured by gas and dust in visible light. Red and blue areas of star formation are visible along the arms, with dark dust lanes wrapping around the galaxy's starry center.

name: NGC 2068  M78
text: This colorful image features a small part of Messier 78, or NGC 2068, a reflection nebula located in the constellation Orion. A reflection nebula is created when light from a star is scattered or reflected off a nearby dust cloud.

name: NGC 1904 M79
text: The globular star cluster Messier 79 is located 41,000 light-years from Earth. It contains about 150,000 stars packed into an area measuring only 118 light-years across. Its stars are some of the oldest in our galaxy.

name: NGC 6093  M80
text: This stellar swarm is Messier 80, one of the densest of the approximately 150 known globular clusters in the Milky Way galaxy. The cluster, also called NGC 6093, contains hundreds of thousands of stars held together by gravity.

name: NGC 3031  M81 Bode's Galaxy
text: The arms of the "grand design" spiral galaxy Messier 81, also called Bode's galaxy or NGC 3031, are filled with young, bluish, hot stars. The greenish regions in the image are bright, gaseous clouds where new stars are forming.

name: NGC 3034   M82 Cigar Galaxy
text: The Cigar galaxy, Messier 82, is remarkable for its bright blue disk, webs of shredded clouds, and fiery-looking plumes of glowing hydrogen blasting out of its central region. In M82, stars are being born 10 times faster than they are inside our Milky Way galaxy.

name: NGC 5236 M83 Southern Pinwheel Galaxy
text: This image of the Southern Pinwheel spiral galaxy, also called Messier 83 or NGC 5236, captures thousands of star clusters, hundreds of thousands of individual stars, and "ghosts" of dead stars called supernova remnants.

name: NGC 4374  M84
text: Discovered in 1781, Messier 84 is an elliptical galaxy located 60 million light-years from Earth in the constellation Virgo. M84, also called NGC 4374, is one of over a thousand galaxies that make up the Virgo cluster.

name: NGC 4382  M85
text: Messier 85, also called NGC 4382, is either an elliptical or a lenticular galaxy. Lenticular galaxies have qualities of both elliptical and spiral galaxies and are sometimes called armless spirals.

name: NGC 4406  M86
text: Messier 86, also called NGC 4406, is either an elliptical galaxy or a lenticular galaxy, which is a cross between an elliptical and spiral galaxy. This image shows about half of the galaxy, including the bright nucleus and surrounding regions of light.

name: NGC 4486  M87 Virgo A
text: Elliptical galaxy Messier 87, or NGC 4486, is the home of several trillion stars and a family of roughly 15,000 globular star clusters. But its most distinctive feature is the jet of subatomic particles speeding from its core, powered by the galaxy's supermassive black hole.

name: NGC 4501 M88
text: Messier 88, or NGC 4501, contains an active galactic nucleus, meaning the central region of the galaxy is more luminous than the rest of the galaxy. At the galaxys core resides a supermassive black hole estimated to be 100 million times more massive than our Sun.

name: NGC 4552  M89
text: Elliptical galaxy Messier 89, or NGC 4552, is almost exactly circular. It contains about 100 billion stars and well over 2,000 globular clusters. Its high population of stars and clusters might be why the galaxy has a larger region of light surrounding it than other elliptical galaxies.

name: NGC 4569  M90
text: Messier 90 is a spiral galaxy situated in the Virgo cluster of galaxies. M90, also called NGC 4569, is believed to be breaking away from the rest of the galaxies in the Virgo cluster and is one of the few galaxies traveling toward our Milky Way galaxy, not away.

name: NGC 4548  M91
text: The spiral galaxy Messier 91, or NGC 4548, is one of over a thousand galaxies that make up the Virgo cluster  a group of galaxies that are gravitationally bound to one another. It is an anemic galaxy, with a lower rate of star formation compared to other spiral galaxies.

name: NGC 6341  M92
text: This Hubble image of Messier 92's core captures the heart of a globular cluster — a ball of stars that orbits our galaxy's center like a satellite. The cluster, also called NGC 6341, is very tightly packed with stars, containing roughly 330,000 in total.

name: NGC 4736  M94  Cat's Eye Galaxy
text: New stars are forming at a high rate within the bright starburst ring of spiral galaxy Messier 94, or NGC 4736. Although M94 was initially believed to be roughly 30,000 light-years in diameter, two faint arms (not shown) were discovered extending far into space, tripling its diameter.

name: NGC 3351   M95
text: Messier 95 is a beautiful, barred spiral galaxy. This image reveals a section of M95, which is also called NGC 3351, featuring its central bar of stars in the upper left and one of its spiral arms extending to the lower right.

name: NGC 3368  M96
text: Dust and gas are unevenly spread throughout Messier 96's weak spiral arms, which are asymmetrical because of its gravitational interaction with neighboring galaxies. M96, or NGC 3368, is also remarkable for the location of its core, which is not exactly at the galactic center.

name: NGC 4192  M98
text: Messier 98, or NGC 4192, is a galaxy of about a trillion stars as well as an abundance of neutral hydrogen gas and interstellar dust. Because of the high amounts of gas and dust, it has numerous star-forming regions, especially in its nucleus and arms.

name: NGC 4254  M99
text: This image shows a detailed view of the spiral arms on one side of the galaxy Messier 99, or NGC 4254. This galaxy is called a grand-design spiral, with long, large, and clearly defined spiral arms.

name: NGC 4321  M100
text: Messier 100, or NGC 4321, is a stunning example of a grand-design spiral galaxy. This image reveals individual stars within the galaxy's prominent spiral arms. M100's arms also host several small black holes, including the youngest one ever observed in our cosmic neighborhood.

name: NGC 5457 Pinwheel Galaxy  M101
text: The Pinwheel galaxy, or Messier 101, has a pancake-like shape that we view face-on. This perspective shows off the spiral structure that gives the galaxy its nickname.

name: NGC 5866 M102 Spindle Galaxy
text: Hubble's sharp vision reveals a crisp dust lane dividing the Spindle galaxy, also known as Messier 102, into two halves. This edge-on view of M102, also called NGC 5866, highlights the galaxy's structure.

name: NGC 4594 M104 Sombrero Galaxy
text: The Sombrero galaxy's hallmark is a brilliant white core encircled by thick lanes of dust. As seen from Earth, the spiral galaxy ― also called Messier 104 or NGC 4594 ― is tilted nearly edge-on.

name: NGC 3379  M105
text: Like most elliptical galaxies, Messier 105, or NGC 3379, appears rather featureless and inactive. However, Hubble revealed young stars and star clusters in M105, indicating that star formation is still taking place.

name: NGC 4258  M106
text: This image of Messier 106, also called NGC 4258, reveals one of the spiral galaxy's most striking features: its extra pair of arms. Most spiral galaxies only have one pair of arms, but M106 has an extra set made of hot gas, seen here as red wisps.

name: NGC 6171  M107
text: Messier 107, or NGC 6171, is one of approximately 150 globular star clusters found around the disk of the Milky Way galaxy. These spherical collections each contain hundreds of thousands of extremely old stars and are among the oldest objects in the Milky Way.

name: NGC 3556 M108 Surfboard Galaxy
text: The Surfboard galaxy, also called Messier 108 or NGC 3556, shows little evidence of a well-defined spiral pattern, but it is classified as a barred spiral galaxy with loosely wound spiral arms. Observations show young star clusters exposed against a mottled and detail-rich background.

name: NGC 205  M110
text: Messier 110 is an elliptical galaxy, which means that it has a smooth and nearly featureless structure. Elliptical galaxies like M110, also called NGC 205, do not have arms or regions of star formation. The stars in elliptical galaxies are often older than those in other galaxies.

name: Leo IV Ultra-Faint Dwarf  Galaxy
text: This image shows some of the stars of Leo IV, one of over a dozen ultra-faint dwarf galaxies near the Milky Way. These galaxies are dominated by dark matter, an invisible substance that makes up most of the universe's mass. Leo IV's stars are almost lost against a tapestry of background galaxies.

name: SDSS J1004+4112 Galaxy Cluster
text: This picture captures a galaxy cluster called SDSS J1004+4112 that's so massive that its gravity bends light from galaxies behind it. The light of a distant quasar (the brilliant core of an active galaxy) has been bent around the cluster, appearing in five places in this image.

name: NGC 4302 and NGC 4298 Spiral Galaxies
text: This image captures two spiral galaxies. They look quite different because we see them from different angles. The edge-on galaxy (bottom) is called NGC 4302, and the other is NGC 4298.

name: NGC 2841 Flocculent spiral
text: Young, blue stars and dark lanes of dust trace the winding arms of NGC 2841. Winds from the young stars may have cleared out the gas needed for additional star birth and halted star formation in the spiral galaxy.

name: Arp 220 Interacting Galaxies
text: Arp 220 is the result of a collision between two spiral galaxies that began 700 million years ago. Located about 250 million light-years from Earth, it is one of the nearest galaxy mergers to our planet.

name: NGC 2976 Spiral Galaxy
text: This picture shows the inner region of NGC 2976, located roughly 11 million light-years away in the constellation Ursa Major. Despite the lack of well-defined arms visible in this image, NGC 2976 is a spiral galaxy.

name: NGC 1427A Galaxy
text: This image captures NGC 1427A, an irregular dwarf galaxy that is warped by the gravitational influence of its larger galactic neighbors in the Fornax galaxy cluster.

name: NGC 2768  elliptical galaxy
text: NGC 2768 is an elliptical galaxy located 65 million light-years away in the constellation Ursa Major. The galaxy hosts a supermassive black hole, fueling jets of material in its active center.

name: NGC 4710 Spiral Galaxy
text: The magnificent galaxy NGC 4710 is tilted nearly edge-on to our view from Earth. This perspective allows the central bulge of stars to be easily distinguished from the galaxy's pancake-flat disk of stars, dust, and gas.

name: AM 0644-741  Lindsay-Shapley Ring Galaxy
text: The striking blue ring of the Lindsay-Shapely Ring galaxy, also called AM 0644-741, is comprised of brilliant star clusters. About 150,000 light-years across, the ring structure is larger than our galaxy, the Milky Way.

name: SN1987A
text: The remnant of Supernova 1987A, located in a neighboring galaxy called the Large Magellanic Cloud, appears at the center of this image. The red, gaseous clouds that surround it fuel a firestorm of new star formation.

name: NGC 4163 Dwarf Galaxy
text: This swarm of stars is the dwarf galaxy NGC 4163, located 10 million light-years from Earth in the constellation Canes Venatici. Irregularly shaped red blobs are regions of active star formation.

name: NGC 1999 Reflection Nebula
text: NGC 1999 is a reflection nebula. It does not emit any visible light of its own but shines only because the light from the star just to the left of the center illuminates the nebula's dust.

name: NGC 4013 Edge-on Spiral Galaxy
text: A dark band of dust bisects the spiral galaxy NGC 4013. This edge-on galaxy is located 55 million light-years away in the constellation Ursa Major.

name: NGC 2787 Galaxy
text: Galaxy NGC 2787 is located 24 million light-years from Earth in the constellation Ursa Major. Arms of dark dust encircle the galaxy's bright center. The points of light scattered around the galaxy are huge collections of old stars known as globuar clusters.

name: NGC 5584 Spiral Galaxy
text: The brilliant, blue glow of young stars traces the graceful spiral arms of galaxy NGC 5584. Thin, dark dust lanes appear to be flowing from the yellowish core, where older stars reside.

name: Starfield in the Large Magellanic Cloud
text: Over 10,000 stars appear in this image, which covers a region about 130 light-years wide in a nearby galaxy called the Large Magellanic Cloud. The faintest stars in the picture are some 100 million times dimmer than the human eye can see.

name: Bow Shock Around LL Orionis
text: Named for the crescent-shaped wave made by a ship as it moves through water, a bow shock can be created in space when streams of gas collide. This image captures the bow shock around the  star LL Orionis.

name: MACS J0717.5+3745  Galaxy Cluster
text: Nearly every object in this image is a distant galaxy in the cluster MACS J0717.5+3745. Some faint arcs and streaks in the image are even farther galaxies whose light has been bent by the powerful gravity of the massive cluster.

name: NGC 2440 Planetary Nebula
text: Planetary nebula NGC 2440 is a relic of a star once like our Sun that has cast off its outer layers of gas, forming a colorful cocoon around the star's remaining core.

name: NGC 2174 Monkey Head Nebula
text: This image reveals carved knots of gas and dust in a small portion of the Monkey Head Nebula. The nebula is a star-forming region that hosts dusky dust clouds silhouetted against glowing gas.

name: Brown Dwarf Candidate CHXR 73 B
text: The bright spot at lower right is a suspected brown dwarf, an object bigger than a planet but smaller than a star. Named CHXR 73 B, it orbits a red dwarf star dubbed CHXR 73, which is much less massive than the Sun.

name: Sharpless 2-106, S106 IR, Sh 2-106 Nebula
text: This star-forming region, called Sharpless 2-106, looks like a celestial angel. The "wings" of the nebula are twin lobes of hot gas that stretch outward from a massive, young star near the center of the image.

name: NGC 6050 ARP 272 IC 1179  Interacting Galaxies
text: Arp 272 is a collision between two spiral galaxies, linked by their swirling arms. The galaxies, also called NGC 6050, are members of the Hercules Galaxy cluster.

name: Zwicky 18 Galaxy
text: This image captures the irregular dwarf galaxy I Zwicky 18 and a companion galaxy to its upper right. The two galaxies are interacting, triggering star formation in I Zwicky 18.

name: Kiso5639_kug1138+327
text: Hubble captured a firestorm of star birth lighting up one end of this dwarf galaxy. Called Kiso 5639, it is a member of a class of "tadpole" galaxies so named because of their bright heads and elongated tails.

name: Herbig-Haro 24 HH 24
text: A partially obscured, newborn star near the center of this image is shooting twin jets into the surrounding gas and dust. The shocks from the collision light up patches of nebulosity collectively called Herbig-Haro 24.

name: NGC 1313 Galaxy
text: This image resolves stars in the center of the barred spiral galaxy NGC 1313. The galaxy is roughly 14 million light-years away in the constellation Reticulum.

name: GOODS-N Galaxies in the GOODS-North Field
text: This image captures about 15,000 galaxies stretching back through 11 billion years of cosmic history. Hubble examined this part of the sky, located near the Big Dipper and called the GOODS-North field, as part of the Great Observatories Origins Deep Survey (GOODS).

name: NGC 6369 Little Ghost Nebula
text: The Little Ghost Nebula appears as a small, ghostly cloud surrounding a dying star. It is found in the constellation Ophiuchus between 2,000 and 5,000 light-years away.

name: Galactic Center
text: This infrared image of the center of our Milky Way galaxy reveals a population of massive stars and complex structures in the hot ionized gas that swirls around the galactic core.

name: SWEEPS Star Field
text: Hubble peered into the crowded central bulge of our galaxy 26,000 light-years away and collected information for 180,000 stars as part of a survey called the Sagittarius Window Eclipsing Extrasolar Planet Search (SWEEPS).

name: RCS2 032727-132623 Galaxy Cluster
text: The light from a distant galaxy, nearly 10 billion light-years away, has been warped into arcs and streaks by the gravity of galaxy cluster RCS2 032727-132623. The cluster acts as a gravitational lens, bending and amplifying light from the background galaxy.

name: NGC 1316 Fornax A Galaxy
text: The dust lanes and star clusters of this giant elliptical galaxy, known as Fornax A or NGC 1316, give evidence that the galaxy formed from a past merger of two gas-rich galaxies. It is also one of the strongest sources of radio emission in the sky.

name: NGC 1512 Galaxy
text: The core of the barred spiral galaxy NGC 1512 is unique for its stunning 2,400-light-year-wide circle of infant star clusters, called a "circumnuclear" starburst ring. Starbursts are episodes of vigorous star formation.

name: Beta Pictoris Disk
text: In 1984, Beta Pictoris was the very first star discovered to be surrounded by a bright disk of light-scattering dust and debris. Planets are thought to form in such disks, and astronomers have discovered two planets orbiting Beta Pictoris.

name: Einstein Ring SDSS J120540.43+491029.3
text: Einstein rings like this object, named SDSS J120540, form when two galaxies are almost perfectly aligned, one behind the other, and the gravitational field of the closer galaxy bends the light from the more-distant galaxy into bright arcs around itself.

name: Abell 2261 Galaxy Cluster
text: The giant elliptical galaxy in the center of this image is the most massive and brightest member of galaxy cluster Abell 2261. More than a million light-years wide, the galaxy is about 10 times bigger than our Milky Way galaxy.

name: Southern Crab Nebula Hen 2-104
text: An aging red giant star is shedding its outer layers to produce the Southern Crab Nebula. The "legs" are likely to be the places where the outflowing material slams into surrounding gas and dust.

name: Einstein Ring SDSS J125028.25+052349
text: Einstein rings like this object, designated SDSS J125028.25+052349, form when two galaxies are almost perfectly aligned, one behind the other, and the gravitational field of the closer galaxy bends the light from the more-distant galaxy into bright arcs around itself.

name: NGC 3310 starburst galaxy
text: There are several hundred star clusters in the starburst galaxy NGC 3310. They appear in this image as the bright, blue clumps that trace the galaxy's spiral arms.

name: NGC 5754 NGC 5752 Arp 297 Interacting Galaxies
text: Arp 297 is a pair of interacting galaxies that consists of NGC 5754, the large spiral at the top, and NGC 5752, the smaller companion at the bottom left. NGC 5754's internal structure has hardly been disturbed, but it does have some kinked arms just beyond its inner ring.

name: NGC 6621 NGC 6622 Arp 81 VV247 Interacting Galaxies
text: Arp 81 is a pair of interacting galaxies consisting of NGC 6621 (center) and NGC 6622 (left). The encounter has pulled a long tail out of NGC 6621 that has now wrapped behind the pair.

name: SN 2002DD Supernova Didius Cosmic Lens  RXJ1532.9+3021
text: Galaxy cluster RXJ1532.9+3021 magnifies the light of the very distant Supernova Didius, the white dot in the center of this image. The bright blob at upper left is the core of the supernova's host galaxy. The supernova is so far away, we see it as it appeared 7 billion years ago.

name: Red Rectangle Nebula HD 44179
text: This image reveals details of one of the most unusual nebulae known in our Milky Way. Cataloged as HD 44179, this nebula is more commonly called the "Red Rectangle" because of its unique shape and color.

name: NGC 6745  Colliding Galaxies
text: This image captures the collision of two galaxies. The larger spiral galaxy, NGC 6745, boasts an intact nucleus as it interacts with the smaller, passing galaxy that is nearly out of the frame to the lower right.

name: UGC 5336 Dwarf Galaxy Holmberg IX
text: This loose collection of stars is actually a dwarf irregular galaxy, called Holmberg IX. Of the more than 20,000 stars that can be resolved in this image, only about 10 percent are considered to be old stars.

name: Interstellar Bubble N44F, 	LHA 120-N 44F
text: This circular feature on the left side of this image is an interstellar bubble called N44F. It is being inflated by a torrent of fast-moving particles from an exceptionally hot star once buried inside this cold, dense cloud.

name: Puppis A Star
text: The bright star RS Puppis is swaddled in a cocoon of reflective dust illuminated by the glittering star. The star is 10 times more massive than our Sun and is 200 times larger.

name: NGC 2080 Ghost Head Nebula in LMC
text: The Ghost Head Nebula is a star-forming region in a nearby galaxy called the Large Magellanic Cloud. The two bright areas (the "eyes of the ghost") are very hot, glowing blobs of hydrogen and oxygen.

name: AM 0500-620 Interacting Galaxies
text: AM 0500-620 includes a pair of galaxies, with one spiral galaxy seen nearly face-on that is partially backlit by a background galaxy. These interacting galaxies are located 350 million light-years away in the constellation Dorado.

name: Arp 274 Interacting Galaxies
text: Arp 274 is a system of three galaxies that appear to be partially overlapping. Two of the galaxies are rapidly forming new stars, evident in the bright blue knots strung along the arms of the galaxy on the right and along the small galaxy on the left.

name: NGC 3314 Galaxy Pair
text: This image shows a pair of galaxies called NGC 3314. Through a chance alignment, a face-on spiral galaxy lies precisely in front of another, larger spiral. This provides a view of dark material within the front galaxy, seen because it is silhouetted against the galaxy behind it.

name: ESO 510-G13 Galaxy  IRAS 13522-2632
text: Usually, when a spiral galaxy appears edge-on, its dust and spiral arms appear flat. The warping of the disk in ESO 510-G13 suggests this galaxy has recently undergone a collision with a nearby galaxy and is in the process of swallowing it.

name: NGC 4650A Polar-ring Galaxy
text: About 130 million light-years away, NGC 4650A is one of only 100 known polar-ring galaxies, which feature a ring of stars encircling a disk. Polar rings might form when two galaxies collide, with one galaxy becoming the inner disk and the other forming the ring.

name: Circinus Galaxy
text: Resembling a swirling witch's cauldron of glowing vapors, the black-hole-powered core of the Circinus galaxy appears in this image. Much of the gas in the spiral galaxy's disk is concentrated in two rings.

name: Hanny's Voorwerp IC 2497
text: This image shows a ghostly green blob of gas that appears to float near a normal-looking spiral galaxy. The bizarre object, dubbed Hanny's Voorwerp, is the visible part of a 300,000-light-year-long streamer of gas stretching around the galaxy, called IC 2497.

name: ESO 99-4, ESO 099-G004 Interacting Galaxies
text: ESO 99-4 is a galaxy with a highly peculiar shape. It is probably the remnant of an earlier merger process that has deformed it, leaving the main body largely obscured by dark bands of dust.

name: Cynus Loop Supernova
text: This image captures a small portion of the Cygnus Loop supernova remnant. The Cygnus Loop marks the edge of a bubble-like, expanding blast wave from a colossal stellar explosion that occurred about 15,000 years ago.

name: N 49 Supernova Remnant LMC  DEM L 190
text: N 49 is a supernova remnant in a neighboring galaxy called the Large Magellanic Cloud. The delicate filaments are sheets of debris from a stellar explosion whose light would have reached Earth thousands of years ago.

name: LMC N 180B,LHA 120-N 180B Nebula
text: N 180B is an active region of star formation in the Large Magellanic Cloud, a dwarf galaxy orbiting our Milky Way. This particular region contains some of the brightest known star clusters.

name: NGC 3982 Spiral Galaxy
text: This image captures the face-on spiral galaxy NGC 3982. Its arms are lined with pink star-forming regions of glowing hydrogen, blue newborn star clusters, and dark dust lanes that provide the raw material for future generations of stars.

name: ESO 239-2 Galaxy
text: ESO 239-2 is the result of a cosmic collision between galaxies that will eventually result in a larger "elliptical" galaxy. The intermediate stage captured here shows a galaxy with long tails of dust and gas that envelop the galaxy's core.

name: Milky Way Bulge Stars in the Galactic Core
text: These colorful stars reside at the heart of our Milky Way galaxy, about 26,000 light-years from Earth. Aging red-giant stars coexist with their more plentiful younger cousins, the smaller, white, Sun-like stars, in this crowded region of our galaxy's central hub.

name: NGC 2264 Cone Nebula
text: The Cone Nebula is a star-forming region in the constellation Monoceros. This conical pillar stretches over seven light-years and is just a small portion of a much larger star-formation complex.

name: NGC 1763 Star-Forming Region N11B LMC
text: This panoramic view captures an iridescent tapestry of star birth, filled with glowing gas, dark dust clouds, and young, hot stars. The star-forming region, cataloged as N11B, lies in a nearby galaxy, the Large Magellanic Cloud.

name: IRAS 19297-0406 Interacting Ultraluminous Infrared Galaxyies (ULIRG)
text: This image shows a tumultuous collision between four galaxies located 1 billion light-years from Earth. The tangled-up galaxies, called IRAS 19297-0406, are crammed together in the center of the picture.

name: Abell 2744  Galaxy Cluster
text: Located 3.5 billion light-years away, Abell 2744 contains several hundred galaxies and might be a pile-up of at least four smaller galaxy clusters. Abell 2744's strong gravitational field acts as a lens, brightening and magnifying the light of nearly 3,000 distant background galaxies.

name: NGC 7173 NGC 7174 NGC 7176 HCG 90 Hickson Compact Group 90
text: These three galaxies, called NGC 7173 (middle left), NGC 7174 (middle right) and NGC 7176 (lower right), are part of Hickson Compact Group 90, named after astronomer Paul Hickson, who cataloged small groups of galaxies like this one.

name: RDCS 1252.9-2927 Galaxy Cluster
text: This image captures a massive cluster of galaxies called RDCS 1252.9-2927. This galaxy cluster existed when the universe was only 5 billion years old, or about 35 percent of its present age.

name: NGC 1748 N83B Nebula in LMC
text: Extremely intense radiation from newly born, ultra-bright stars has blown a glowing, spherical bubble in the nebula NGC 1748. The average-looking star at the very center of the bubble is about 30 times more massive and almost 200,000 times brighter than our Sun.

name: NGC 4622 Face-on Spiral Galaxy
text: This image shows the spiral galaxy NGC 4622. Its outer pair of winding arms is full of new stars, clumped together in blue clusters. Strangely, the galaxy appears to be rotating clockwise, the opposite direction to what astronomers expected.

name: 3C 273 Quasar
text: The quasar 3C 273 resides at the heart of a galaxy nearly 2 billion light-years away. A quasar is a brilliant source of energy at the center of a distant galaxy, and is believed to flare up when gas, dust, or other material falls onto a supermassive black hole at the galaxy's core.

name: NGC 6782 Galaxy
text: This spiral galaxy, NGC 6782, exhibits tightly wound spiral arms and a spectacular, nearly circular bright ring surrounding its nucleus. The ring contains many recently formed hot stars.

name: NGC 7674, Markarian 533, HCG 96 Arp 182, Interacting Galaxies
text: NGC 7674 is a spiral galaxy tilted nearly face-on to Earth. Faint streamers below and to the left of the galaxy have been created by gravitational interactions with companion galaxies.

name: Abell 1689  Galaxy Cluster
text: This image shows the inner region of Abell 1689, an immense cluster of galaxies located 2.2 billion light-years away. Astronomers used Hubble to map the distrubition of dark matter in the galaxy cluster.

name: VY Canis Majoris Star HD 58061, HIP 35793
text: The hypergiant star VY Canis Majoris is surrounded by clouds of gas that it has cast off in a long series of outbursts. These eruptions have formed loops, arcs, and knots of material moving at various speeds and in many different directions.

name: NGC 7318A 7318B 7319 7320 HCG 92 Stephan's Quintet
text: This close-up shows four of the five galaxies that make up Stephan's Quintet. The image reveals bright, blue clusters of stars, born from the violent interactions between some of the member galaxies.

name: AM 2026-424 Interacting Galaxies
text: The colliding galaxies AM 2026-424 resemble a face. Each "eye" is the bright core of a galaxy, one of which slammed into another. The outline of the face is a ring of young blue stars. Other clumps of new stars form a nose and mouth.

name: Arp 142 Interacting Galaxies
text: The interacting galaxy duo near the bottom of this image is Arp 142. The pair contains the disturbed, star-forming spiral galaxy NGC 2936 along with its elliptical companion NGC 2937 to the left. To the right is an unrelated, bluish galaxy called UGC 5130.

name: Extended Groth Strip (EGS)
text: This field of galaxies is just a small part of a cosmic tapestry Hubble imaged as part of the All-wavelength Extended Groth Strip International Survey. In it are galaxies of all shapes, sizes, colors, and distances. Larger ones are nearby, while the smallest ones are far away.

name: SN 2002dd Supernova HDF-N
text: This image captures a stellar explosion called a supernova in a small part of the sky known as the Hubble Deep Field. The supernova, designated SN 2002dd, appears as a red dot near the center of the image.

name: Seyfert's Sextet HCG 79, UGC 10116, NGC 6027
text: At first, Seyfert's Sextet looks like six galaxies grouped closely together. However, the small galaxy with the prominent spiral arms (right of center) is much farther away than the others, and a bright clump to the lower right is material torn from one of the other galaxies.

name: MC2 1635+119 Quasar
text: This image shows shells of stars around a quasar known as MC2 1635+119. Quasars are among the brightest objects in the universe. They reside in the centers of galaxies and are powered by supermassive black holes.

name: Ant Nebula Mz 3
text: The Ant Nebula displays intriguing symmetrical patterns in the lobes of gas being ejected from a dying Sun-like star at its center.

name: PN G054.2-03.4 Necklace Nebula
text: The Necklace Nebula contains the glowing remains of an ordinary, Sun-like star shedding material at the end of its life. The nebula consists of a bright ring, measuring 12 trillion miles across, dotted with dense, bright knots of gas that resemble diamonds in a necklace.

name: NGC 5189 Planetary Nebula
text: The  knotty, filamentary structure of NGC 5189 formed as a dying star shed its outer layers. Interestingly, this planetary nebula has two nested structures tilted with respect to each other.

name: Hoag's Object Galaxy
text: A nearly perfect ring of hot, blue stars pinwheels about the yellow nucleus of an unusual galaxy known as Hoag's Object. Curiously, a background object that bears an uncanny resemblance to Hoag's Object can be seen in the gap at the one o'clock position.

name: NGC 4068 Dwarf Galaxy
text: This image captures a starburst region in the dwarf galaxy NGC 4068. Starburst regions are areas of intense star formation.

name: UGC 06471 and UGC 06472 Interacting Galaxies
text: This image shows a cosmic collision between two galaxies, UGC 06471 and UGC 06472. The colliding galaxies are 145 million light-years from Earth. Such collisions distort the shapes of the galaxies as they merge and eventually form a larger galaxy.

name: TN J1338-1942 Galaxy Cluster
text: The galaxy cluster TN J1338-1942 contains a massive embryonic galaxy surrounded by smaller developing galaxies. The central galaxy has spectacular radio-emitting jets, fueled by a supermassive black hole deep within the galaxy's nucleus.

name: NGC 346 Star Cluster in SMC
text: This image captures a dynamic star-forming region in a nearby dwarf galaxy called the Small Magellanic Cloud. At the center is a brilliant star cluster called NGC 346.

name: NGC 300 Spiral Galaxy
text: NGC 300 is a spiral galaxy similar to our own Milky Way galaxy. Some of the bright blue specks in this image are young, massive stars called blue supergiants, and they are among the brightest stars seen in spiral galaxies.

name: AM 1316-241 Interacting Galaxies
text: AM 1316-241 is made up of two interacting galaxies: a spiral galaxy (on the left) in front of an elliptical galaxy (on the right). The starlight from the background elliptical galaxy is partially obscured by bands and filaments of dust in the foreground spiral galaxy.

name: Protostar IRAS 20324+4057
text: This caterpillar-shaped knot, called IRAS 20324+4057, is a protostar that is in the process of growing from the dust and gas surrounding it. However, other bright stars are blasting ultraviolet radiation at this "wanna-be" star and sculpting the gas and dust into its long shape.

name: HCG 87 Hickson Compact Group 87
text: This troupe of galaxies, known as Hickson Compact Group 87, is performing an intricate dance orchestrated by the mutual gravitational forces acting between them. The small spiral near the center could either be a member or an unrelated background object.

name: Trumpler 14 Star Cluster
text: Called Trumpler 14, this cluster of stars is located 8,000 light-years away in a huge star-forming region known as the Carina Nebula. The cluster is only 500,000 years old and has one of the highest concentrations of bright, massive stars in the entire Milky Way.

name: Engraved Hourglass Nebula, MyCn18
text: The Hourglass Nebula has been formed by a dying Sun-like star shedding its outer layers of gas. One theory suggests that the hourglass shape is produced as a fast stellar wind encounters a slowly expanding cloud that is more dense near the star's equator than near its poles.

name: NGC 1672 Galaxy
text: NGC 1672 is a barred spiral galaxy. Its arms do not twist all the way to the galaxy's center but attach to the ends of a bar of stars that extends from the nucleus. Clusters of hot, young, blue stars form along the spiral arms, while surrounding clouds of hydrogen gas glow red.

name: NGC 2074 Nebula in LMC
text: The nebula NGC 2074 is a firestorm of raw stellar creation, perhaps triggered by a nearby supernova explosion. It lies in a nearby galaxy called the Large Magellanic Cloud, about 170,000 light-years away.

name: NGC 1808 Starburst Galaxy
text: This close-up view shows a hotbed of star formation at the center of spiral galaxy NGC 1808. In the image, older stars appear yellow and young stars are blue.

name: NGC 6503 Galaxy
text: Most galaxies are clumped together in groups or clusters. A neighboring galaxy is never far away. But this galaxy, known as NGC 6503, has found itself in a lonely position, at the edge of a strangely empty patch of space called the Local Void.

name: NGC 4993 lenticular galaxy
text: In this galaxy, called NGC 4993, two neutron stars collided, creating gravitational waves discovered in 2017. The event produced a flash of light, called a kilonova, which appears to the upper left of center.

name: Herbig Haro 32, HH 32
text: This is an example of a "Herbig-Haro object," which is formed when young stars eject jets of material back into interstellar space. These jets plow into the surrounding nebula, producing strong shock waves that heat the gas and cause it to glow.

name: UDF
text: This image of the Hubble Ultra Deep Field includes infrared observations that allowed Hubble to peer deeper into the universe than it ever had before. The faintest and reddest objects in the image are galaxies that formed 600 million years after the big bang.

name: HUDF-JD2 Galaxy
text: The small red object at the center of this image (just above the large spiral galaxy) is one of the most distant galaxies ever seen. Called HUDF-JD2, it is one of about 10,000 galaxies found in the Hubble Ultra Deep Field.

name: N 81 Nebula SMC
text: This image shows a newborn star cluster cradled within a nebula, or glowing cloud of gas, called N 81. This stellar nursery lies about 200,000 light-years away within the Small Magellanic Cloud, a small galaxy orbiting our own Milky Way.

name: V838 Monocerotis Star Light Echo
text: These images capture a light echo from the star V838 Monocerotis. After the star brightened temporarily, light from that eruption began propagating outward through a dusty cloud around the star. The light reflects or "echoes" off the dust and then travels to Earth.

name: Arches Cluster
text: The Arches cluster is the densest known star cluster in our galaxy and resides 25,000 light-years away. In this rough-and-tumble region, huge clouds of gas collide to form behemoth stars.

name: UGC 5340 Dwarf Galaxy
text: This image captures the dwarf galaxy UGC 5340. A pocket of rapid star birth appears in the lower right corner. This region of star formation was probably triggered by a gravitational interaction with an unseen companion galaxy.

name: IC 349 Reflection Nebula, Barnard's Merope Nebula
text: IC 349 is a reflection nebula in the Pleiades star cluster (often called the "Seven Sisters"). The eerie, wispy tendrils of an interstellar cloud are being destroyed by one of the brightest stars in the star cluster.

name: GOODS-S
text: More than 12 billion years of cosmic history are shown in this panoramic view of thousands of galaxies in various stages of assembly. The view covers a portion of the southern field of a galaxy census called the Great Observatories Origins Deep Survey (GOODS).

name: ESO 243-49 Galaxy
text: This edge-on galaxy, called ESO 243-49, appears to host a medium-sized black hole that might have come from a cannibalized dwarf galaxy. As massive as 20,000 Suns, the black hole lies above the galactic plane — an unusual location that suggests it originated somewhere else.

name: NGC 1132 Galaxy
text: The large elliptical galaxy NGC 1132 likely formed from a group of galaxies that merged together. The galaxy is dubbed a "fossil group" because it contains enormous concentrations of dark matter, comparable to the dark matter found in an entire group of galaxies.

name: Egg Nebula  CRL 2688
text: In the Egg Nebula, shells of dust form concentric rings around an aging star, resembling the layers of an onion. A thick dust belt, running almost vertically through the center, blocks light from the central star while twin beams of light radiate from the star.

name: NGC 3949 Spiral Galaxy
text: Like our Milky Way, the galaxy NGC 3949 has a disk full of young, blue stars peppered with pink star-birth regions. In contrast to the blue disk, the galaxy's bright center is made up of mostly older stars and appears more yellow.

name: Radio Galaxy Hercules A 3C 348
text: At the center of this image sits a large galaxy called Hercules A that harbors a supermassive black hole more than a thousand times as massive as the one in the Milky Way's center. Radio observations reveal large jets shooting away from the galaxy's core.

name: Abell 2667 Galaxy Cluster
text: While looking at galaxy cluster Abell 2667, astronomers found an odd-looking spiral galaxy (in the upper left corner of the image) that is plowing through the cluster and being ripped apart by the galaxy cluster's gravitational field and harsh environment.

name: Cl 0024+1654 Galaxy Cluster
text: The light from a distant galaxy, nearly 10 billion light-years away, has been warped into blue arcs and streaks by the gravity of galaxy cluster 0024+1654. The cluster's gravity acts as a lens, bending and amplifying light from the background galaxy.

name: E0102 Supernova Remnant SMC,  1E0102.2-7219
text: In a nearby galaxy called the Small Magellanic Cloud, a massive star exploded as a supernova and dissipated its interior into a spectacular display of colorful filaments. The supernova remnant, known as E0102, is the greenish-blue field of debris just below center.

name: Cartwheel Galaxy, ESO 350-40, AM0035-335
text: The unusual appearance of the Cartwheel galaxy (right) was created by a nearly head-on collision with a smaller galaxy. Its spoke-like structures are wisps of material connecting the galaxy's nucleus to an outer ring of young stars.

name: N30B Reflection Nebula  DEM L 106
text: A unique, peanut-shaped cocoon of dust surrounds a cluster of young, hot stars in this image. This reflection nebula, named N30B, is embedded in a much larger nebula called DEM L 106. The wispy filaments of DEM L 106 fill much of the image.

name: NGC 1569 Galaxy
text: The nearby dwarf galaxy NGC 1569 is a hotbed of vigorous star birth and is one of the closest "starburst" galaxies to us. The galaxy's "star factories" are manufacturing brilliant blue star clusters.

name: Horsehead Nebula, Barnard 33
text: The backlit wisps along the Horsehead Nebula's upper ridge are being illuminated by a young five-star system just off the top of this image, taken in infrared light. Harsh radiation from one of these bright stars is slowly evaporating the nebula.
